The Sierra Club alleges that Minnesota Power has broken the Clear Air Act nearly 13,000 times since 2009 at three coal plants&nbsp;in northern Minnesota.&nbsp;
The environmental group made the allegations in a letter to Minnesota Power executives. According to the Star Tribune, the Sierra Club threatened litigation over measurements showing high opacity levels, which it links&nbsp;to high levels of soot.&nbsp;
The Duluth-based company, however, contends that the plants operate under opacity limits 99.7 percent of the time&nbsp;and that high opacity levels don't necessarily mean higher pollution levels. The Minnesota Pollution Control Agency agrees, and told the Star Tribune it doesn't plan enforcement action.&nbsp;
The three plants are in Boswell, Taconite Harbor and Laskin, Minn.&nbsp;
